<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-11-09T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-11-09T19:00:00-05:00" n="447" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d447">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">125.956/37</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-11-09T19:00:00-05:00">November 9, 1937—7
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>346. Reference Allison’s Nov. 8, 2 p.m., from Tsingtao. Provided you
                            consider it advisable, the Department has no objection to Allison’s <pb facs="0384" n="376" xml:id="pg_376"/> remaining temporarily at
                            Tsinan to handle any urgent and important matters which require
                            attention, but feels that he should, upon the completion of emergency
                            duties, return to Nanking to report and to discuss with you the subject
                            matter of the telegram under reference.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>